This is the show exploring
the mysteries and the science

00:00:21.588 --> 00:00:24.124 line:57%
of the amazing
human brain.

00:00:24.224 --> 00:00:26.760 line:71%
What does it mean to be
the best at something?

00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:29.996 line:71%
To simply be better at it
than everyone else?

00:00:30.096 --> 00:00:31.498 line:71%
For one man from
South Georgia,

00:00:31.598 --> 00:00:34.634 line:71%
being the best
led him to the NFL.

00:00:34.734 --> 00:00:37.504 line:71%
The path to success
was punishing.

00:00:37.604 --> 00:00:39.873 line:71%
And in the process,
Nate Lewis will tell you,

00:00:39.973 --> 00:00:41.808 line:71%
he lost who he was.

00:00:41.908 --> 00:00:45.078 line:71%
Now he is on a journey to try
to help his brain function

00:00:45.178 --> 00:00:46.613 line:71%
like it used to.

00:00:46.713 --> 00:00:53.253 line:0%
♪♪

00:00:53.353 --> 00:00:55.588 line:64%
<i> In his suburban
 Atlanta neighborhood,</i>

00:00:55.688 --> 00:00:58.491 line:64%
<i> Nate Lewis tackles
 the asphalt hills.</i>

00:00:58.591 --> 00:01:03.730 line:64%
<i> Each painful step a reminder
 of the price of love.</i>

00:01:03.830 --> 00:01:05.932 line:71%
<i> For Lewis,
 that love affair began</i>

00:01:06.032 --> 00:01:08.201 line:71%
<i> when he was just
 10 years old,</i>

00:01:08.301 --> 00:01:11.304 line:71%
<i> growing up in the South
 Georgia town of Moultrie.</i>

00:01:11.404 --> 00:01:13.173 line:68%
<i> (Nate)
 It's all about
 football down there.</i>

00:01:13.273 --> 00:01:15.141 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 It was the
 football field.</i>

00:01:15.241 --> 00:01:18.178 line:71%
A green oasis in a town
baked and browned

00:01:18.278 --> 00:01:20.146 line:71%
by relentless summers.

00:01:20.246 --> 00:01:21.281 line:71%
<i> (Nate)
 I was just, like,</i>

00:01:21.381 --> 00:01:23.783 line:71%
<i> obsessed with the-the
 smell of the grass.</i>

00:01:23.883 --> 00:01:25.218 line:71%
<i> And so I would just
 get up in the morning</i>

00:01:25.318 --> 00:01:28.088 line:71%
<i> and put my cleats on, and
 just go run on the grass.</i>

00:01:28.188 --> 00:01:31.858 line:71%
If it was fresh-cut,
oh, that was emotional.

00:01:31.958 --> 00:01:34.260 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 It was on the grass
 that Lewis,</i>

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:36.796 line:71%
<i> and everyone who
 watched him play,</i>

00:01:36.896 --> 00:01:39.199 line:71%
<i> realized he had a gift.</i>

00:01:39.299 --> 00:01:40.733 line:71%
<i> (Nate)
 And I was outrunning them.</i>

00:01:40.834 --> 00:01:42.669 line:71%
I would jump
higher than them.

00:01:42.769 --> 00:01:44.437 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 A running back
 turned wide receiver,</i>

00:01:44.537 --> 00:01:47.107 line:71%
<i> his senior year at
 Colquitt County High School,</i>

00:01:47.207 --> 00:01:50.143 line:71%
<i> Lewis was recruited to
 the University of Georgia.</i>

00:01:50.243 --> 00:01:52.545 line:64%
<i> Nathaniel Lewis of
 Moultrie, Georgia,</i>

00:01:52.645 --> 00:01:54.481 line:71%
<i> high in the air.</i>

00:01:54.581 --> 00:01:56.282 line:60%
<i> (Jaye)
 With the ball tucked
 under his arm,</i>

00:01:56.382 --> 00:01:58.985 line:64%
<i> his beloved green field
 spread before him,</i>

00:01:59.085 --> 00:02:02.055 line:64%
<i> Lewis was unstoppable.</i>

00:02:02.155 --> 00:02:03.356 line:57%
<i> (Nate)
 You hear your heartbeat.</i>

00:02:03.456 --> 00:02:04.891 line:64%
You hear yourself breathing,

00:02:04.991 --> 00:02:06.226 line:64%
<i> Then you don't
 hear nothin'.</i>

00:02:06.326 --> 00:02:08.394 line:64%
<i> No, you just focus on
 where you have to go.</i>

00:02:08.495 --> 00:02:10.463 line:64%
<i> Yeah, that's what
 I love to do.</i>

00:02:10.563 --> 00:02:12.065 line:53%
<i> (Jaye)
 By the time Lewis
 was scoring</i>

00:02:12.165 --> 00:02:13.867 line:57%
<i> against Georgia Tech
 and Clemson,</i>

00:02:13.967 --> 00:02:16.936 line:71%
<i> he says he had already
 suffered concussions.</i>

00:02:17.036 --> 00:02:19.305 line:71%
<i> Although they didn't
 call them concussions.</i>

00:02:19.405 --> 00:02:21.875 line:71%
<i> It was "getting
 your bell rung."</i>

00:02:21.975 --> 00:02:24.444 line:71%
<i> (Nate)
 About 14-- 13, 14 years old.</i>

00:02:24.544 --> 00:02:25.845 line:71%
You actually
do see stars.

00:02:25.945 --> 00:02:28.615 line:71%
You can't see.
You can't focus.

00:02:28.715 --> 00:02:30.917 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Lewis remembers what
 the coaches would say.</i>

00:02:31.017 --> 00:02:31.918 line:68%
<i> (Nate)
 Like, he said,
 "You all right?</i>

00:02:32.018 --> 00:02:32.919 line:71%
<i> "You all right?"</i>

00:02:33.019 --> 00:02:34.053 line:64%
<i> I was like, "No."</i>

00:02:34.154 --> 00:02:35.622 line:57%
He was like,
"Well, come on,

00:02:35.722 --> 00:02:38.258 line:57%
"just take a--
take one play off."

00:02:38.358 --> 00:02:40.393 line:57%
I took a play off.
I wasn't right.

00:02:40.493 --> 00:02:44.597 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 And then,
 the NFL came calling.</i>

00:02:44.697 --> 00:02:46.533 line:71%
<i> In the NFL,
 everyone is fast.</i>

00:02:46.633 --> 00:02:47.534 line:71%
Everybody's fast.

00:02:47.634 --> 00:02:49.736 line:71%
Everything's
happening quicker.

00:02:49.836 --> 00:02:53.206 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 A childhood passion
 had led him to the top.</i>

00:02:53.306 --> 00:02:55.842 line:71%
<i> In his six years playing
 for the San Diego Chargers</i>

00:02:55.942 --> 00:02:59.746 line:71%
<i> and the Chicago Bears,
 the hits kept coming.</i>

00:02:59.846 --> 00:03:02.849 line:71%
<i> How did they treat you for
 a concussion when you got one?</i>

00:03:02.949 --> 00:03:04.450 line:71%
Ice.

00:03:04.551 --> 00:03:07.053 line:71%
On top of my head
or on my neck.

00:03:07.153 --> 00:03:08.421 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 In the NFL?</i>

00:03:08.521 --> 00:03:09.455 line:71%
Oh, yeah.

00:03:09.556 --> 00:03:11.925 line:71%
<i> And besides ice?</i>

00:03:12.025 --> 00:03:13.326 line:71%
That's it.

00:03:13.426 --> 00:03:14.327 line:71%
That was it.

00:03:14.427 --> 00:03:16.930 line:71%
That's the only t--
treatment I got.

00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:19.599 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 A pastime was
 now serious business.</i>

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:21.467 line:71%
<i> Lewis says he
 played through pain</i>

00:03:21.568 --> 00:03:23.770 line:71%
<i> and confusion so severe,</i>

00:03:23.870 --> 00:03:27.473 line:71%
<i> there are entire days of
 his career that are a blank.</i>

00:03:29.008 --> 00:03:31.744 line:71%
<i> His wife, Sherry,
 reminds him of one time.</i>

00:03:31.844 --> 00:03:33.880 line:57%
The one that you got
on the plane, and--

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:34.914 line:64%
That was Denver.

00:03:35.014 --> 00:03:36.049 line:64%
That was Denver.

00:03:36.149 --> 00:03:40.186 line:57%
And he said that he doesn't
remember the trip home.

00:03:40.286 --> 00:03:44.023 line:71%
<i>He, um, you know,
didn't know where he was.</i>

00:03:44.123 --> 00:03:46.159 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Seven years after
 he left football,</i>

00:03:46.259 --> 00:03:48.628 line:71%
<i> Sherry says,
 Nate changed.</i>

00:03:48.728 --> 00:03:50.930 line:71%
<i> He would get enraged
 over nothing.</i>

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:54.167 line:71%
<i> A drawer left open,
 a shoe on the floor.</i>

00:03:54.267 --> 00:03:56.603 line:71%
Very argumentative.

00:03:56.703 --> 00:03:59.539 line:71%
Lack of communication.

00:03:59.639 --> 00:04:01.074 line:71%
He built a wall.

00:04:01.174 --> 00:04:02.875 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 What else did you see?</i>

00:04:02.976 --> 00:04:05.545 line:71%
<i>(Sherry)
Confusion.</i>

00:04:05.645 --> 00:04:09.682 line:71%
A look in his eye that
just didn't feel the same.

00:04:09.782 --> 00:04:11.684 line:71%
We had a good connection.

00:04:11.784 --> 00:04:15.255 line:71%
And it just
seemed like...

00:04:15.355 --> 00:04:17.690 line:71%
he wasn't there anymore.

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:19.692 line:71%
And he didn't love me.

00:04:19.792 --> 00:04:22.061 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 It didn't take much
 to set him off.</i>

00:04:22.161 --> 00:04:24.297 line:71%
<i> Did you feel
 a lot of rage?</i>

00:04:24.397 --> 00:04:25.598 line:71%
<i> (Nate)
 Yes.</i>

00:04:25.698 --> 00:04:28.067 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 What were you mad about?</i>

00:04:28.167 --> 00:04:29.602 line:71%
<i> (Nate)
 Not being able to do--</i>

00:04:29.702 --> 00:04:32.839 line:71%
<i> not being able to
 hold a thought.</i>

00:04:32.939 --> 00:04:34.641 line:71%
Not being able to
hold a thought.

00:04:34.741 --> 00:04:37.076 line:57%
And because, um,
it's like, you know,

00:04:37.176 --> 00:04:39.946 line:57%
I don't want my wife
to think I'm dumb.

00:04:40.046 --> 00:04:41.214 line:57%
You know, I've been
to college.

00:04:41.314 --> 00:04:43.950 line:57%
I-I was able to do
these type of things.

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:45.551 line:71%
But I can't
do it no more.

00:04:45.652 --> 00:04:47.987 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Sherry would learn
 Nate was suicidal,</i>

00:04:48.087 --> 00:04:51.224 line:71%
<i> and thought often of crashing
 the 18-wheeler trucks</i>

00:04:51.324 --> 00:04:53.293 line:71%
<i> he now drove to
 make a living.</i>

00:04:53.393 --> 00:04:57.930 line:71%
If I was to just drive off
this-drive off this cliff,

00:04:58.031 --> 00:05:00.533 line:71%
everything exploded,
I'd be-- that'd be it.

00:05:00.633 --> 00:05:02.602 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 They were on
 the brink of divorce.</i>

00:05:02.702 --> 00:05:04.337 line:71%
<i> Then came the
 turning point.</i>

00:05:04.437 --> 00:05:06.939 line:57%
Junior Seau was one of
the best-known players

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:08.441 line:64%
in the NFL during...

00:05:08.541 --> 00:05:10.510 line:71%
An apparent suicide
by a powerful athlete,

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:12.679 line:71%
a force of nature on
the football field.

00:05:12.779 --> 00:05:16.149 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Junior Seau, Nate Lewis'
 Chargers teammate and friend,</i>

00:05:16.249 --> 00:05:17.817 line:71%
<i> killed himself.</i>

00:05:17.917 --> 00:05:19.385 line:71%
<i> It was heartbreaking,</i>

00:05:19.485 --> 00:05:22.555 line:71%
<i> because the story that
 they told behind that</i>

00:05:22.655 --> 00:05:25.792 line:71%
and the struggle that
he was goin' through.

00:05:25.892 --> 00:05:28.861 line:71%
And I'm like, "Wow, I'm goin'
through the same stuff."

00:05:28.961 --> 00:05:32.365 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 The autopsy would show
 Seau's brain had CTE,</i>

00:05:32.465 --> 00:05:34.801 line:71%
<i> Chronic Traumatic
 Encephalopathy.</i>

00:05:34.901 --> 00:05:37.470 line:71%
<i> A progressive degenerative
 disease of the brain</i>

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:40.907 line:71%
<i> found in people with a history
 of repetitive brain trauma,</i>

00:05:41.007 --> 00:05:42.942 line:71%
<i> such as concussions.</i>

00:05:43.042 --> 00:05:44.544 line:71%
<i> How many concussions
 have you had?</i>

00:05:44.644 --> 00:05:46.112 line:71%
I can't count.

00:05:46.212 --> 00:05:47.413 line:71%
I can't really count.

00:05:47.513 --> 00:05:50.550 line:71%
I mean, 'cause--

00:05:50.650 --> 00:05:52.151 line:64%
<i> Five?</i>

00:05:50.650 --> 00:05:52.151 line:71%
More.

00:05:52.251 --> 00:05:54.187 line:64%
<i> Ten?</i>

00:05:52.251 --> 00:05:54.187 line:71%
More.

00:05:54.287 --> 00:05:55.688 line:71%
<i> Twenty?</i>

00:05:55.788 --> 00:05:57.957 line:71%
Yeah, about--
I'd say about that.

00:05:58.057 --> 00:06:00.560 line:71%
Probably more.
Twenty or more.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:03.029 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Nate and Sherry say Junior
 saved their marriage,</i>

00:06:03.129 --> 00:06:04.797 line:71%
<i> and Nate's life.</i>

00:06:04.897 --> 00:06:06.132 line:71%
<i> He got help.</i>

00:06:06.232 --> 00:06:08.735 line:71%
<i> He now takes medicine to
 deal with the headaches,</i>

00:06:08.835 --> 00:06:13.139 line:71%
<i> depression, anger,
 and attention issues.</i>

00:06:13.239 --> 00:06:14.474 line:71%
<i> All right,
 how you doing today?</i>

00:06:14.574 --> 00:06:15.641 line:57%
Good.
How about yourself?

00:06:15.742 --> 00:06:17.777 line:71%
I am good.
Glad to see you.

00:06:17.877 --> 00:06:18.978 line:64%
Same here.

00:06:19.078 --> 00:06:20.313 line:53%
<i> (Jaye)
 At Emory Brain
 Health Center,</i>

00:06:20.413 --> 00:06:23.916 line:57%
<i>he is doing ecologically-related
neurorehabilitation,</i>

00:06:24.016 --> 00:06:26.386 line:57%
<i> to try to help his brain
 function better.</i>

00:06:26.486 --> 00:06:27.854 line:71%
<i>"Write the names down.</i>

00:06:27.954 --> 00:06:29.956 line:71%
<i>Distinguish the physical
facts of the person."</i>

00:06:30.056 --> 00:06:31.424 line:71%
<i> Okay, good.</i>

00:06:31.524 --> 00:06:33.326 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 W-O-P-R.</i>

00:06:33.426 --> 00:06:36.863 line:71%
<i> Write, Organize,
 Picture, Rehearse.</i>

00:06:36.963 --> 00:06:38.431 line:71%
<i> This is Nate's life.</i>

00:06:38.531 --> 00:06:40.533 line:71%
He takes a notebook
everywhere.

00:06:40.633 --> 00:06:42.235 line:71%
<i> Writes what he
 needs to remember,</i>

00:06:42.335 --> 00:06:45.004 line:71%
<i> organizes it,
 paints a mental picture,</i>

00:06:45.104 --> 00:06:47.840 line:64%
<i> and rehearses recalling
 the information.</i>

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:51.010 line:64%
<i> Today, Nate is working on
 remembering names and faces.</i>

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:54.180 line:64%
<i> Do you remember
 this guy's name, here?</i>

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:56.582 line:71%
<i> (groans)</i>

00:06:56.682 --> 00:06:58.951 line:71%
Hmm?

00:06:59.051 --> 00:07:01.754 line:71%
We talked about
the moustache.

00:07:01.854 --> 00:07:04.891 line:71%
<i>Larry, um...</i>

00:07:04.991 --> 00:07:07.093 line:71%
I remember he played
tennis, right?

00:07:07.193 --> 00:07:08.461 line:71%
He played tennis.

00:07:08.561 --> 00:07:10.329 line:71%
Larry Carlton.

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:11.898 line:71%
<i> Larry Carlton.
 That's right.</i>

00:07:11.998 --> 00:07:13.433 line:64%
Boo-yah.

00:07:11.998 --> 00:07:13.433 line:71%
<i> Good job.</i>

00:07:13.533 --> 00:07:15.301 line:64%
<i> Excellent work.</i>

00:07:13.533 --> 00:07:15.301 line:71%
Yeah, yeah.

00:07:15.401 --> 00:07:17.737 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 It's not the thrill
 of a touchdown,</i>

00:07:17.837 --> 00:07:19.539 line:71%
<i> but it is a victory.</i>

00:07:19.639 --> 00:07:22.108 line:71%
<i> And those happen rarely
 for Lewis, these days.</i>

00:07:22.208 --> 00:07:23.209 line:71%
<i> (Dr. Tony Stringer)
 Well, certainly,</i>

00:07:23.309 --> 00:07:24.644 line:71%
<i> our nervous system has
 tremendous capacity</i>

00:07:24.744 --> 00:07:26.179 line:71%
<i> to heal itself.</i>

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:27.647 line:57%
What we do in
rehabilitation

00:07:27.747 --> 00:07:31.017 line:57%
is we try to facilitate
that spontaneous recovery.

00:07:31.117 --> 00:07:32.351 line:57%
And-- but even
more importantly,

00:07:32.452 --> 00:07:34.921 line:57%
particularly when we're talking
about cognitive abilities,

00:07:35.021 --> 00:07:37.056 line:71%
<i> what we're really trying
 to do is to teach people</i>

00:07:37.156 --> 00:07:40.526 line:71%
<i>to make really good use of their
preserved cognitive skills.</i>

00:07:40.626 --> 00:07:42.428 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 This rehab isn't new.</i>

00:07:42.528 --> 00:07:44.730 line:71%
<i> Emory Neuropsychologist,
 Dr. Tony Stringer,</i>

00:07:44.831 --> 00:07:46.833 line:71%
<i> used it with patients who
 suffered brain injuries</i>

00:07:46.933 --> 00:07:48.968 line:71%
<i> in car accidents
 20 years ago.</i>

00:07:49.068 --> 00:07:52.038 line:71%
<i> He developed WOPR
 and other strategies</i>

00:07:52.138 --> 00:07:54.507 line:71%
<i> that help patients like Nate
 deal with reasoning,</i>

00:07:54.607 --> 00:07:57.243 line:71%
<i> problem solving,
 and attention deficiencies.</i>

00:07:57.343 --> 00:07:59.779 line:71%
<i> That's why athletes concerned
 about their concussions</i>

00:07:59.879 --> 00:08:02.281 line:71%
<i> are now seeking out
 Dr. Stringer.</i>

00:08:02.381 --> 00:08:05.184 line:71%
Stringer's research is showing
some remarkable outcomes

00:08:05.284 --> 00:08:08.087 line:71%
<i> in brains of patients
 diagnosed with MCI,</i>

00:08:08.187 --> 00:08:11.991 line:71%
<i> Mild Cognitive Impairment,
 an early form of dementia.</i>

00:08:12.091 --> 00:08:14.694 line:71%
<i> Working with researchers now
 at the University of Michigan</i>

00:08:14.794 --> 00:08:16.429 line:71%
<i> and Penn State
 University,</i>

00:08:16.529 --> 00:08:20.433 line:71%
<i> they compared people with MCI
 to people with healthy brains.</i>

00:08:20.533 --> 00:08:22.935 line:71%
<i> The orange indicates
 activity in the brain</i>

00:08:23.035 --> 00:08:24.537 line:71%
<i> while they perform task.</i>

00:08:24.637 --> 00:08:25.905 line:71%
<i> In the MCI brains,</i>

00:08:26.005 --> 00:08:27.807 line:71%
<i> far fewer areas
 are lighting up</i>

00:08:27.907 --> 00:08:30.009 line:71%
<i> before cognitive
 rehabilitation.</i>

00:08:30.109 --> 00:08:31.711 line:71%
These brains are from
patients who actually

00:08:31.811 --> 00:08:33.946 line:71%
have gone through
cognitive rehabilitation.

00:08:34.046 --> 00:08:35.114 line:71%
And you can see,

00:08:35.214 --> 00:08:37.250 line:71%
they look a lot more like
the healthy controls.

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:39.986 line:71%
A lot more activation in
the frontal part of the brain,

00:08:40.086 --> 00:08:42.855 line:71%
which is the part of the brain
that really becomes engaged

00:08:42.955 --> 00:08:45.191 line:71%
when we're using a
strategy to compensate

00:08:45.291 --> 00:08:46.792 line:71%
for memory
difficulties.

00:08:46.893 --> 00:08:48.528 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Essentially, other
 parts of the brain</i>

00:08:48.628 --> 00:08:50.096 line:71%
<i> can pick up the slack</i>

00:08:50.196 --> 00:08:52.698 line:71%
<i> for parts that no longer
 function as they should.</i>

00:08:52.798 --> 00:08:55.034 line:71%
<i> What researchers know
 about the long-term impact</i>

00:08:55.134 --> 00:08:58.604 line:71%
<i> of concussions on a brain
 is constantly evolving.</i>

00:08:58.704 --> 00:09:00.573 line:71%
<i> The research is
